{
  "title": "The end of Roman Britain",
  "keyStage": "ks1",
  "subject": "history",
  "learningOutcome": "I can describe what changed in Britain when Roman rule ended.",
  "learningCycles": [
    "Recall the main reasons why Roman rule in Britain ended.",
    "List the immediate changes that occurred in Britain following the departure of Roman forces.",
    "Evaluate the longer-term cultural impacts of the end of Roman rule."
  ],
  "priorKnowledge": [
    "The Roman Empire extended into Britain, impacting its culture and infrastructure.",
    "The timeline of Roman Britain, including key dates such as the invasion in 43 CE and Roman withdrawal around 410 CE.",
    "The concept of Romanisation, highlighting how Roman culture influenced local populations.",
    "Basic understanding of the hierarchical structure of the Roman Empire, including governors overseeing provinces.",
    "Awareness of local tribes and their interactions with Roman settlers."
  ],
  "keyLearningPoints": [
    "Roman Britain ended around 410 CE, marked by Emperor Honorius's decision to withdraw Roman troops from British territories.",
    "The absence of Roman military protection led to increased invasions and raids by groups such as the Picts, Scots, and Saxons.",
    "The departure of Roman governance caused political fragmentation, with local leaders and tribal chiefs gaining control.",
    "Roman infrastructure, including roads, buildings, and baths, became neglected without ongoing maintenance.",
    "For several centuries after Roman rule ended, Britain experienced significant cultural and social transformations blending Roman and native influences."
  ],
  "misconceptions": [
    {
      "misconception": "Roman Britain ended abruptly when all infrastructure collapsed",
      "description": "While Roman authority ceased around 410 CE, many Roman structures continued to be used for centuries, albeit without maintenance."
    },
    {
      "misconception": "All cultural aspects of Roman life disappeared from Britain post-410 CE",
      "description": "Several Roman cultural practices and artefacts persisted, blending with local traditions to create a unique cultural evolution."
    },
    {
      "misconception": "The withdrawal of Rome's armies left Britain immediately defenceless",
      "description": "Rome's withdrawal was gradual, and local leaders managed defences, albeit with less coordination than under direct Roman rule."
    }
  ],
  "keywords": [
    {
      "keyword": "Romanisation",
      "definition": "The adoption of Roman culture, language, and customs by local populations in Britain during Roman rule"
    },
    {
      "keyword": "Province",
      "definition": "A territory governed as a part of the Roman Empire, managed by officials appointed by the empire"
    },
    {
      "keyword": "Picts",
      "definition": "A group of tribes from present-day Scotland known for their invasions of Roman Britain towards its end"
    },
    {
      "keyword": "Saxons",
      "definition": "A confederation of Germanic tribes that began to settle in Britain following the end of Roman rule"
    },
    {
      "keyword": "Infrastructure",
      "definition": "Essential facilities and structures, such as roads and buildings, supporting societal functions"
    }
  ],
  "starterQuiz": {
    "version": "v3",
    "questions": [
      {
        "question": "Identify the time during which the Romans commenced their rule over Britain.",
        "hint": "To provide a clue, consider the events around 43 CE.",
        "questionType": "multiple-choice",
        "answers": [
          "43 CE"
        ],
        "distractors": [
          "54 BCE",
          "410 CE"
        ]
      },
      {
        "question": "What term describes the influence of Roman culture and practices on local British populations?",
        "hint": "This term reflects the adoption of Roman culture such as language and customs.",
        "questionType": "multiple-choice",
        "answers": [
          "Romanisation"
        ],
        "distractors": [
          "Governance",
          "Civilisation"
        ]
      },
      {
        "question": "Select the structure Roman governors utilised to manage the territories within Britain.",
        "hint": "Think about the administrative divisions of the Roman Empire.",
        "questionType": "multiple-choice",
        "answers": [
          "Provinces"
        ],
        "distractors": [
          "Settlements",
          "Colonies"
        ]
      },
      {
        "question": "Which group from Northern Britain frequently engaged in conflicts with Roman forces?",
        "hint": "This group resided in the area now recognised as Scotland.",
        "questionType": "multiple-choice",
        "answers": [
          "Picts"
        ],
        "distractors": [
          "Gauls",
          "Angles"
        ]
      },
      {
        "question": "What major infrastructural development did Romans introduce to Britain to connect key settlements?",
        "hint": "These provided significant mobility and trade advantages.",
        "questionType": "multiple-choice",
        "answers": [
          "Roads"
        ],
        "distractors": [
          "Canals",
          "Aqueducts"
        ]
      },
      {
        "question": "During which century did the Roman forces withdraw from their rule in Britain?",
        "hint": "This event occurred approximately around 410 CE.",
        "questionType": "multiple-choice",
        "answers": [
          "5th Century"
        ],
        "distractors": [
          "3rd Century",
          "6th Century"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "imageMetadata": [],
    "reportId": ""
  },
  "cycle1": {
    "title": "The fall of Roman rule in Britain",
    "durationInMinutes": 8,
    "explanation": {
      "spokenExplanation": [
        "Explain that in around 410 CE, Roman authority in Britain officially came to an end as the Roman Empire faced significant challenges elsewhere.",
        "Highlight that Emperor Honorius advised the cities of Britain to manage their own defences, effectively ending Roman governance.",
        "Discuss how without Roman military support, Britain became vulnerable to various external invasions and internal strife.",
        "Mention that the infrastructure put in place by the Romans, such as roads and baths, began to deteriorate due to lack of maintenance.",
        "Finally, provide examples of Roman cultural remnants that persisted, such as artefacts and language influences."
      ],
      "accompanyingSlideDetails": "A timeline marking 410 CE as the end of Roman rule in Britain alongside an illustration of Roman roads and ruins.",
      "imagePrompt": "Timeline depicting the collapse of Roman rule in Britain",
      "slideText": "Roman authority in Britain ended around 410 CE, leaving local communities to manage independently."
    },
    "checkForUnderstanding": [
      {
        "question": "What year is commonly associated with the end of Roman rule in Britain?",
        "answers": [
          "410 CE"
        ],
        "distractors": [
          "400 CE",
          "450 CE"
        ]
      },
      {
        "question": "What advice did Emperor Honorius give to the cities in Britain?",
        "answers": [
          "To defend themselves independently"
        ],
        "distractors": [
          "To seek aid from neighbouring tribes",
          "To migrate south for safety"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "practice": "Create a timeline showing the key events that led to the end of Roman rule in Britain. Include important years, such as 43 CE for the invasion and 410 CE for the withdrawal.",
    "feedback": "Model answer: The timeline should start with the Roman invasion of Britain in 43 CE, continue with notable Roman activities, and end with the withdrawal around 410 CE."
  },
  "cycle2": {
    "title": "The fall of Roman infrastructure and governance",
    "durationInMinutes": 8,
    "explanation": {
      "spokenExplanation": [
        "Introduce how the departure of Roman governance led to changes in administration as Britain lacked a unified leadership.",
        "Explain the neglect of infrastructure, such as roads and buildings, that were no longer maintained.",
        "Discuss how the end of centralised Roman law and order led to increased localism and the rise of regional leaders.",
        "Provide examples of Roman legacies that persisted, like Latin vocabulary in the language and architectural remnants."
      ],
      "accompanyingSlideDetails": "An illustration displaying Roman roads and ruins alongside a breakdown of administrative changes post-Roman rule.",
      "imagePrompt": "A depiction of Roman ruins and maps illustrating localised governance after Roman rule.",
      "slideText": "As Roman control ended, Britain saw administrative changes, neglected structures, and a move to local leaderships."
    },
    "checkForUnderstanding": [
      {
        "question": "What was a major administrative change when Roman rule ended in Britain?",
        "answers": [
          "The rise of regional leaders."
        ],
        "distractors": [
          "Increased Roman military presence.",
          "Introduction of a new written language."
        ]
      },
      {
        "question": "What happened to Roman roads after the Romans left Britain?",
        "answers": [
          "They fell into neglect."
        ],
        "distractors": [
          "They were improved upon.",
          "They were destroyed."
        ]
      }
    ],
    "practice": "Think about how Britain might have changed after Roman rule ended. Write two sentences describing how the lack of Roman administration and military affected the landscape and society.",
    "feedback": "Model Answer: Without Roman administration, local leaders took on governance. Roman roads and buildings were neglected, changing their appearances and uses over time."
  }
}

